Theorem~\ref{thm:macrob holds away from the vacuum, i.e., for $\rho>0$, and under the following set of assumptions: for any $\rho>0$ and $h>0$ we have \begin{equation}\label{e:p} p \in\C1([0,\infty)), \qquad p(0)=0, \qquad p'(\rho) > 0,\end{equation}
\begin{equation}\label{e:V} V \in\C2([0,\infty)), \qquad V(0)=0, \qquad V'(h) > 0,\end{equation}
\begin{equation}\label{e:pV} V(h) \neq \rho \, p'(\rho) \, V'(h), \qquad \rho \, p'(\rho)^2 \, V''(h) < \left( 2 p'(\rho) + \rho \, p''(\rho) \right) V'(h), \intertext{and there exist $c_{\min},c_\infty>0$ and $\xi_i$, $i\in\disint{1,p} \coloneqq [1,p] \cap \Z$, with $\xi_i<\xi_{i+1}$ such that for almost any $x\in\R$} \label{e:c} c\in \Lloc1(\R) \cap \C2( \R \setminus \{\xi_1,\ldots,\xi_p\}), \qquad c-c_\infty \in \L1(\R), \qquad c(x) \geq c_{\min}.\end{equation}.}

